        <mo>=</mo>
        <mn>0.</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle R_{\mu \nu }=0.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="../I/f767d26db25b97adb1a1bb7264bac5df6653f344.svg" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline mw-invert" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -1.005ex; width:8.766ex; height:2.843ex;" alt="{\displaystyle R_{\mu \nu }=0.}" loading="lazy"></span></dd></dl>

<p id="mwAVo">In general relativity, the <a href="World_line" title="World line" id="mwAVs">world line</a> of a particle free from all external, non-gravitational force is a particular type of geodesic in curved spacetime. In other words, a freely moving or falling particle always moves along a geodesic.</p>

<p id="mwAVw">The <a href="Geodesics_in_general_relativity" title="Geodesics in general relativity" id="mwAV0">geodesic equation</a> is:</p>
<dl id="mwAV4"><dd id="mwAV8"><span class="mwe-math-element" id="mwAWA"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\displaystyle {d^{2}x^{\mu } \over ds^{2}}+\Gamma ^{\mu }{}_{\alpha \beta }{dx^{\alpha } \over ds}{dx^{\beta } \over ds}=0,}">
